s fully-updated and revised second edition, authors Michael A. Livingston, Pier Giuseppe Monateri, and Francesco Parisi describe the substantial changes in Italian law and society in the intervening five decades-including the creation and impact of the European Union, as well as important advances in comparative law methodology. The second edition poses timely, relevant questions of whether and to what extent the unique Italian style of law has survived the pressures of European unification, American influence, and the globalization of law and society in the intervening period. The Italian Legal System, Second Edition is an important and stimulating resource for those with specific interest in Italy and those with a more general interest in comparative law and the globalization process.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aLawxItalyxItaly. 0aLawzItaly. 4aItalian government. 4aItalian history. 4aItalian legal system. 4acivil law. 4acivil procedure. 4acomparative law. 4aglobalization. 4alegal institutions. 7aLAW / Comparative.2bisacsh1 aMonateri, Pier Giuseppe, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aParisi, Francesco, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804796552zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804796552423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804796552.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles